{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530544"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:08:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:08:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14551"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14551"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.7,0.13,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7244"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90056"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3039"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by her partner. She has a two-week history of depressed mood, anhedonia, poor sleep with early morning awakening, and fatigue. For the past three days, she has been expressing beliefs that she is responsible for a recent natural disaster and that the world would be better off without her. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She denies any substance use. On examination, she appears distressed with a flat affect. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Mental state examination reveals thought blocking and poverty of speech. There is no evidence of perceptual disturbances or formal thought disorder.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delusional disorder","Major depressive disorder with psychotic features","Brief psychotic disorder","Schizoaffective disorder","Schizophrenia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emajor depressive disorder with psychotic features\u003C/strong\u003E. The stem describes a two-week history of depressive symptoms along with psychotic symptoms (delusions of guilt and worthlessness) that are congruent with her depressed mood. To meet DSM-5 criteria for major depressive episode, a patient must have at least one of the two major criteria (depressed mood or anhedonia) plus at least five of the following nine symptoms present during the same two-week period: (1) depressed mood - present, (2) anhedonia - present, (3) insomnia with early morning awakening - present, (4) significant weight loss - present, (5) fatigue - present, (6) feelings of worthlessness/inappropriate guilt - present, (7) psychomotor retardation - present, (8) diminished ability to think or concentrate, and (9) recurrent thoughts of death. This patient clearly meets both major criteria and has seven of the nine symptoms, fulfilling the diagnostic requirements. The presence of mood-congruent delusions (believing she is responsible for a natural disaster) indicates psychotic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizophrenia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a longer duration of psychotic symptoms (at least six months) and would include positive symptoms such as hallucinations or disorganized speech, which are not evident in this case. The predominant mood symptoms and the mood-congruent nature of the delusions make schizophrenia less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelusional disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by the presence of one or more delusions for at least one month in the absence of other psychotic symptoms or significant mood symptoms. In this case, the prominent depressive symptoms and the short duration of delusions (three days) make delusional disorder an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizoaffective disorder\u003C/strong\u003E requires the presence of a major mood episode concurrent with symptoms that meet Criterion A for schizophrenia, as well as delusions or hallucinations for two or more weeks in the absence of a major mood episode. In this case, the psychotic symptoms appear to be entirely mood-congruent and have not persisted independently of the mood episode.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrief psychotic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves the sudden onset of psychotic symptoms lasting more than one day but less than one month. While the duration of psychotic symptoms in this case (three days) could fit this diagnosis, the presence of significant mood symptoms and the mood-congruent nature of the delusions make major depressive disorder with psychotic features a more appropriate diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that mood disorders with psychotic features can be challenging to differentiate from other psychotic disorders, especially in their early stages. Careful longitudinal assessment and observation of the course of symptoms are often necessary for a definitive diagnosis. Treatment typically involves a combination of antidepressants and antipsychotic medications, along with close monitoring and supportive psychotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mood disorders with psychotic features can present with delusions or hallucinations that are congruent or incongruent with the mood state.","The presence of psychotic symptoms in a mood disorder does not necessarily indicate schizophrenia or schizoaffective disorder.","Treatment of mood disorders with psychotic features typically involves a combination of mood stabilizers or antidepressants and antipsychotic medications."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association DS, American Psychiatric Association DS. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders: DSM-5. Washington, DC: American psychiatric association; 2013 May 22."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90056"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14551"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90056"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T10:47:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T11:07:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7244"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}